         <abstract>
            <p>This record refers to a collection of Miracles of the Trinity attributed to
               <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS2748BeduaA">Bǝḍuʿa ʾAmlāk</persName>, described in the following paragraphs. It is different from
               <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2286ZenaSellase">Zenā nagaromu la-Śǝllāse</ref> (the collection of prayers to the Trinity
               <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2296Sayfas">Sayfa Śǝllāse</ref> arranged according
               to the days of the week together with miracles of the Trinity)
               and from  <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2282Trinity">Taʾammǝra Śǝllāse</ref> (a collection of miracles of the 
               Trinity transmitted with <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT1300Dersan">Dǝrsāna Śǝllāse</ref>).</p>
            <p>
               From     <bibl corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/CDVHURR9"><seg type="encyclopediaArticle"><!-- attributes from original bibl--></seg><ptr target="bm:Nosnitsin2010EAETammeraS"/><title level="a">Täʾammǝrä sǝllase</title><title type="short">EAe</title><title level="m">Encyclopaedia Aethiopica</title><author><forename>Denis</forename><surname>Nosnitsin</surname></author><editor><forename>Siegbert</forename><surname>Uhlig</surname></editor><editor><forename>Alessandro</forename><surname>Bausi</surname></editor><pubPlace>Wiesbaden</pubPlace><publisher>Harrassowitz Verlag</publisher><date>2010</date><biblScope unit="volume">IV</biblScope><biblScope unit="page">975-976</biblScope><note type="tags"><note type="tag">bm:Nosnitsin2010EAETammeraS</note></note><note type="tag">bm:Nosnitsin2010EAETammeraS</note></bibl> (minimally rephrased):
            While described as “Miracles”, the work does
            not exactly conform to the form of <foreign xml:lang="gez">taʾammǝr</foreign>
            known otherwise. It is a re-narration of the Biblical history from the
            Creation to Num 17 (“rod of Aaron”), divided
            according to subjects. God is everywhere represented
            as the Trinity (relevant verbal forms being
            conjugated in 3rd pers. masc. pl.), also before the
            Creation (since the existence of the Father did
            not precede that of the Son and the Holy Spirit).
            Thus the author reconsiders and re-narrates different
            episodes of the O.T. from the “triadologic”
            point of view.
         </p>
            <p>The text contains the story of
               the "pearl" (<foreign xml:lang="gez">baḥrǝy</foreign>), i.e. St <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS6819Mary">Mary</persName>, contained in
               Adam's body</p>
            <p>This work is attested in <ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/BerOrQuart993">Berlin, Berlin State Library, Ms. or. quart. 993</ref> and
               <ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/EMML4769">Collegeville, Hill Museum and Manuscript Library, MS EMML no. 4769</ref>.</p>
           </abstract>
         
